@NODE Requirements "3.1  Requirements"
@{u}@{b}3.1 Requirements@{uu}@{ub}

@{u}Minimum:@{uu}

· Kickstart and Workbench 2.04 or later.
· MUI 3.1 or later.
· Memory usage depends on your configuration, for example whether you want
  IntuiCookie to have a background pattern, but should not exceed 300k.
· ±400 kilobytes on your HD.  (Only ±25 kilobytes have to reside on your
  boot partition.)

@{u}Optimal@{uu}

· 68020 or better
· Fast RAM
· Up to 7 MB of HD space, depending on your cookie file. ;-)

@ENDNODE





@NODE Installation "3.2  Installation"
@{u}@{b}3.2  Installation@{uu}@{ub}

· Just drag this drawer anywhere you like.
· Drag the IntuiCookie executable in the WBStartup drawer.
· Run IntuiCookie.
· It will open open an Error message.  Click on "Continue"
  and type the name of your cookiefile in the string gadget
  (if you just want to test, "data/cookies" should be OK)
  and click on "Save".
· Congratulations!  IntuiCookie is now installed!

@{u}De-Install@{uu}

Delete the IntuiCookie drawer and the IntuiCookie executable
and type:
delete envarc:mui/IntuiCookie#?
in a Shell.

@ENDNODE





@NODE Usage "4.1  Usage"
@{u}@{b}4.1  Usage@{uu}@{ub}

WORKBENCH

Simply start it by clicking on its icon.
A window will be opened, click on "Exit" to close it, or on "Next" to
display the next cookie.  You can also take a look at the @{"menus" LINK Menus}.

IntuiCookie can be customised via the @{"Prefs" LINK Prefs} and the MUI prefs program.


SHELL

Simply enter its name in a Shell window.
A cookie will be printed.

There are two command line options:

· GUI   : open the GUI and behave just as if started from Workbench
· PREFS : open the Prefs window (don't display cookie)

@ENDNODE





@NODE Menus "4.2 Menus"
@{b}@{u}4.2 Menus@{ub}@{un}


@{b}@{u}Project menu@{uu}@{ub}

@{u}About@{uu}
· A requester with the version number, a giftware notice and my contact
  address will appear.  Click on Continue to close the requester.

@{u}Quit@{uu}
· Will have the same effect as clicking on the close or Continue gadgets:
  Close the window and quit.

@{b}@{u}Edit menu@{uu}@{ub}

@{u}Update hashfile@{uu}
· Update the hashfile, use the values set in the Prefs.

@{u}Cookiefile Info@{uu}
· Will display informations about the cookiefile.
  This data can be found in the first lines of the cookiefiles,
  everything before the first '%' is considered as Info text.

@{u}Cookie Info@{uu}
· Will display the number of cookies in the file, the number of
  the current cookie and the size in bytes, including and
  excluding the size of the origin text (if any).

@ENDNODE





@NODE Prefs "5.1 Prefs"
@{b}@{u}5.1 Prefs@{uu}@{ub}

The Prefs window is divided into five registers.

On the top of those registers is the string gadget that
determines the name of the cookiefile.

Below the registers, there are three buttons to Save
the config, just use it or discard changes.

@{u}WB Formatting@{uu}

Divided into two parts: Cookie Preparse and Origin Preparse.
Used to determine how the cookie or origin text should be
formatted when shown in a window.

@{u}CLI Formatting@{uu}

 Divided into two parts: Cookie Preparse and Origin Preparse.
Used to determine how the cookie or origin text should be
formatted when printed to the Shell.

@{u}Hashfile@{uu}

This register configures the hashfile creator.  Here you
can set:

Maximum lines: Defines the maximum of lines you want your cookies
               to have.

Maximum characters per line: Defines the maximum of characters
                             per line you want your cookie to have.

Show progress report: Open a window and display a progress report
                      while updating the hashfile?

Display info: Open a window with some statistics after the hashfile
              has been updated.

Progress report update: Tells IC how often to update the gauge in
                        the process report.  This will heavily
                        influence the speed at which the hashfile is
                        generated. On my config:
                        1     : 26 minutes
                        10    : 4 minutes
                        100   : 25 seconds
                        1000  : 9 seconds
                        10000 : 7 seconds
                        If no window is opened, it will take 5 secs.

Update hashfile: Recreate the hashfile.  Whenever you change
                 some options in the hashfile register, you
                 need to click on this.

@{u}Window elements@{uu}

Display Origin: Chose if you want to see the origins of the cookies
Next Button:    Chose if you want to see the [Next] button
Exit button:    Chose if you want to see the [Exit] button
Window:         Enable/disabel different elements in the window.

@{u}Headers & footers@{uu}

Workbench: Before Cookie: A text to display in front of a cookie
           Before Origin: A text to display in front of an origin

CLI: Before Cookie: A text to display in front of a cookie
     Before Origin: A text to display in front of an origin

You can use formatting codes, a description is below these elements.

@ENDNODE





@NODE CookieFileFormat "5.2 Format of the cookie files"
@{b}@{u}5.2 Format of the cookie files@{uu}@{ub}

The cookie file is a plain ASCII text file which can be read and modified
by any text editor.  Individual cookies can occupy up to 1024 bytes (± 12
lines) and are separated by a line containing nothing but two percent
signs.

Example:

---BEGIN OF FILE---
About the cookie file
%
First cookie.
%
Second
cookie!
%
This
is the
third cookie
---END OF FILE---

Note that there's are no separators before the first and after the last
cookie!

@{u}Formatting characters@{uu}
"@b" - Print the following characters in bold.
"@i" - Print the following characters in italics.
"@u" - Underline the following characters.
"@c" - Center the following lines.
"@l" - Align the following lines to the left.
"@r" - Align the following lines to the right.
"@2" to "@8" - Use color X for the following characters.
             - The only useful value is 8, this will highlight
               the cookie.
"@n" - Switch back to normal text.

The cookie mustn't be longer than 1024 characters.

Note that all text before the first '%%' is considered as Info Text, which
can be displayed using the "Cookiefile Info" @{"menu" LINK Menus}.

When adding cookies that come with an origin, please use the following
format for the origin:
- The name has to be on its own line.
- It must be preceeded by two hyphens and one space ("-- ").
- It must not be longer than 1024 characters.
If you don't follow these conventions, IntuiCookie may have problems
recognising origins.
@ENDNODE





@NODE FortuneCookie "6.1 What is a fortune cookie?"
@{b}@{u}6.1 What is a fortune cookie?@{uu}@{ub}

A fortune cookie is a random quote, item of trivia, joke or maxim printed
to the users terminal at login time.
-- Quoted from Jargon 3.0.0

@ENDNODE



@NODE CookieFile "6.2 What is a cookie file?"
@{b}@{u}6.2 What is a cookie file?@{uu}@{ub}

A cookie file is a collection of @{"fortune cookies" LINK FortuneCookie} in a format
that facilitates retrieval by a fortune program.
There are several different cookie files in public distribution, and site
administrators often assemble their own from various sources.
-- Quoted from Jargon 3.0.0

@ENDNODE





@NODE HashFile "6.3 What is a hash file?"
@{b}@{u}6.3 What is a hash file?@{uu}@{ub}

A hash file is a file containing nothing but hexadecimal numbers (the
"coordinates" where a new cookie begins) used for amazingly fast access
of @{"fortune cookies" LINK FortuneCookie}, even in large files.
@ENDNODE





